column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY OCCURRED. THE PACKAGE WAS BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLERS NOTICED LEAKAGE COMING FROM THE CONTAINER. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 12 AEROSOL CANS OF VARIOUS TYPES OF FLAMMABLE SOLVENTS AND CLEANERS FOR AUTOMOTIVE USE. THE ITEM WAS PICKED UP BY VEHICLE IN CLEVELAND OHIO AND TRANSITED ON 05/01/2002 BY AIR ON FEDEX FLT-1631 (CLE-IND) AND OUT ON THE AM OF 05/02/2002 ON FEDEX FLT-1705 (IND-OAK). THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKING OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE ITEM WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE TSA/FAA FOR INVESTIGATION. TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT KATHLEEN ROSCHER/TSA/FAA/SFO/CASFO ON 05/06/2002 AT 16:46 (CST).

WHILE AT THE WILSON TRUCK CORPORATION FACILITY IN CONLEY, GEORGIA, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM A TWO-HUNDRED AND TWENTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC TOTE.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF ATLANTA, GA RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICE OF ATLANTA, GA RECOVERED TWO, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS OF FREE PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING TOTE.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF ATLANTA, GA, RECOVERED FIVE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED PRODUCT.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF ATLANTA, GA WILL DISPOSE OF ALL WASTE GENERATED.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: CLINT WEAVER WAS HEADING EAST BOUND OUT OF TEXAS.  MR. WEAVER WAS EXITING AT THE LA SCALES AT MILE MARKER 2 AT 30-35 MPH IN POSTED SPEED ZONE OF 35MPH.  ONCE ON THE SCALE HOUSE ROAD HE TURNED HIS LIGHTS OFF.  AFTER TURNING HIS LIGHTS OFF HE NOTICED THAT THERE WERE NO STREET LIGHTS ON PATHWAY TO SCALE.  UPON NOTICING THIS HE FELT THE CAUTIONARY BUMPS AND ATTEMPTED TO TURN BACK INTO ROADWAY.  AT THIS POINT HE WAS ALREADY DOWN THE EMBANKMENT AND HIS BACK TIRES HAD ALREADY GONE OFF THE ROADWAY.  THE PRODUCT SHIFTING AND DRIVER TRYING TO GET BACK ONTO ROADWAY CAUSED EQUIPMENT TO ROLL OVER ONTO PASSENGER SIDE OF TRUCK.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: ON APRIL 30TH, 2002 ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AT A CUSTOMER SITE PACKAGED 18X1 GALLON CONTAINERS OF 20% HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND 4% PEROXYACETIC ACID SOLUTION INTO A 55 GALLON LINED METAL DRUM.  THESE ONE GALLON CONTAINERS WERE ORIGINALLY PLACED ON A PALLET IN A WAREHOUSE SETTING AND WERE STRUCK INTO WITH A FORKLIFT.  THE FOLLOWING AFTERNOON WHILE THE DRUM WAS IN TRANSIT AT THE ONYX AZUSA 10-DAY LOCATION, THIS DRUM STARTED TO VENT A GAS TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  ONYX PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO IT IMMEDIATELY AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE INNER(1 GALLON) CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING CAUSING THE OXYGEN GAS TO BE LIBERATED.  THESE LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE RE-PACKED INTO ANOTHER DRUM ACCORDING TO ALL DOT REQUIREMENTS.  THERE WERE NO SPILLS OR INJURIES.
HEAVY RAINS CAUSED OIL THAT WAS IN THE FILL CONTAINERS TO SPILL OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  (UNKNOWN HOW THE OIL GOT INTO THE CONTAINER)

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE THAT LED TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY OCCURRED. THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 12 PLASTIC INNER UNITS AT 16 OZS. EACH OF A SUBSTANCE CALLED ' FLY PEL ' AN INSECT REPELLENT SPRAY(NON AEROSOL) FOR HORSES. WARNINGS ON THE LEAKING CONTAINER'S LABEL INDICATED "FLAMMABLE: KEEP  AWAY FROM HEAT AND OPEN FLAME" AN MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND OBTAINED FROM THE MANUFACTURER OF THE MATERIAL. THE FLASH POINT INDICATED WAS 110'F CLEARLY MEETING THE DEFINITION OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID IN PACKING GROUP III. THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE SURFACE OF THE OUTER BOX NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION. TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT ALAN EDWARDS/FAA/DEN/CASFO AT 16:00 (CST) ON 05/21/2002.

column168: WEST BOUND ON HEY. 40, 0430, 5-20-2002. DRIVER SAW ANIMAL LAYING IN THE ROAD, IT APPEARED DEAD. TRIED TO AVOID RUNNING OVER, BUT HIT ANIMAL WITH RIGHT SIDE TIRES ON TRACTOR. DRIVER THOUGHT HE MISSED ANIMAL. THE ANIMAL WHICH TURNED OUT TO BE A BEAVER HIT THE BOTTOM DUMP HATCH TIGHTENING BOLTS. THE BOLT ON THE REAR POD WAS PUSHED OUT OF THE TIGHTENING BRACKET ALLOWING THE HATCH TO OPEN, SPILLING A.N. DOWN THE HIGHWAY 2 MILES BEFORE ANOTHER TRUCK CALLED ON THE RADIO THAT OUR UNIT WAS LOSING PRODUCT. DRIVER STOPPED AND RE-CLOSED HATCH AND CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE AND TO REPORT THE SPILL. THE TIGHTENING BOLTS WERE CUT OFF TO INCREASE THE ROAD CLEARANCE TO 13".  A HOLE WAS DRILLED THROUGH THE METAL BRACKET AND A SAFETY BOLT  INSTALLED. THE TIGHTENING BOLT CANNOT COME OUT OF THE HATCH BRACKET WITHOUT REMOVING THE SAFETY BOLT.

column168: THIS UNIT WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HIGHWAY 301.  IT WAS BEHIND A FLATBED TRACTOR TRAILER.  AS THE FLATBED NEARED AN ENTRANCE TO A PLANT, HE SUDDENLY SLOWED DOWN.  THE INFINGER DRIVER TRIED TO STOP, BUT WAS UNABLE TO DO SO CAUSING THE UNIT TO SWERVE LEFT AND OVERTURNED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER ATTACHED DELIVERY LIQUID HOSE TO STORAGE TANK AND CARGO TANK. PRESSURE HOSE UP STARTED PUMP TO TRANSFER PRODUCT.  WITHIN 2-3 MINUTES OF TRANSFER TIME, THE DELIVERY HOUSE RUPTURED.  THE HOLE WAS APPROXIMATELY 3/8" IN THE HOSE.  CO2 WAS RELEASED THROUGH THIS HOLE.  DRIVER TURNED OFF PUMP AND CLOSED VALUES ON CARGO TANK AND STORAGE TANK IMMEDIATELY.  ONCE PRESSURE HAD VENTED FROM THE HOSE THE HOSE WAS DISCONNECTED.  THE HOSE WAS NOT REPAIRED AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON MAY 3, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 1840 HOURS, RAILCAR NAHX 320523 LOADED WITH SODIUM PERCARBONATE WAS OBSERVED FOAMING AND LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED TO THE OFFICE CAR TRACK, AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  MSDEQ, THE JACKSON FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE SHIPPER'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM REPORTED THAT THE CAR APPEARED TO BE OVERLOADED, AND THAT THE SPILLAGE ON TOP AND SIDES OF THE CAR WAS THE EXTENT OF THE INCIDENT.  NO REACTION OF MATERIAL WAS FOUND. RESIDUE WAS CLEANED FROM THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE CAR.  NARRI = 5(5+3+0)X(2+0)=80 CODE = 717 (OVERFILLING)

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE WHEN IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. STANDARD SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION DUE TO LOOSE CLOSURES ON TWO OF THE INNER CONTAINERS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THIS TO BE RETURNED.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A SAFETY-KLEEN DELIVERY TRUCK WAS TRAVELING BETWEEN DESTINATIONS BETWEEN DESTINATIONS, UPON ARRIVAL TO THE DOLTON,  IL FACILITY IT WAS OBSERVED THAT A ONE GALLON SPILL OF WASTE PAINT RELATED MATERIALS HAD SPILLED ONTO THE CARGO BED OF THE VEHICLE. THE SPILL RESULTED FROM A LOOSE LID OF A 55-GALLON METAL OPEN TOP DRUM. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED USING ABSORBENT PADS AND MATERIALS WHICH WERE CONTAINERIZED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY TEN POUNDS OF WASTE MATERIAL WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY LOCATED AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, ILLINOIS. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER LOADING AND DRUM CLOSURE TECHNIQUES TO ENSURE THAT NO FUTURE INCIDENTS WILL OCCUR.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: A SAFETY-KLEEN CARGO VAN WAS BEING UNLOADED AT A TEN DAY TRANSFER FACILITY WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE 55-GALLON METAL DRUM HAD RELEASED APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF WASTE PETROLEUM DISTILLATES ONTO THE CARGO BED OF THE TRAILER.  THE SPILL RESULTED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK IN THE CONTAINER.  THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A PINHOLE RESULTING FROM METAL FATIGUE. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY SEVEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS CONTAINERIZED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY LOCATED AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD IN SMITHFIELD, KENTUCKY.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND LOADING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO FUTURE INCIDENTS WILL OCCUR.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: A SAFETY-KLEEN DELIVERY TRUCK WAS BEING UNLOADED AT THE FACILITY WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE QUARTER OF ONE GALLON OF WASTE TETRACHLOROTHYLENE HAD SPILLED ONTO THE CARGO BED OF THE TRUCK.  THE SPILL RESULTED FROM A LOOSE LID ON THE CONTAINER.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FOUR POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WILL BE DISPOSED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY LOCATED AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE SE IN HEBRON, OHIO.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER BLOCKING AND DRUM CLOSURE TECHNIQUES TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS FROM OCCURRING.
WHEN OPENED TRAILER NOTICED DRUM ON SIDE + LIQUID ON FLOOR.  NEUTRALIZED W/ BAKING SODA AND SENT FREIGHT ONTO CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.
FOUND WHILE UNLOADING, PULLED AWAY FROM DOCK, SHUT DOOR AND ISOLATED. GARNER ENV RESPONDED FOR CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

DURING ROUTINE INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION, TANK CAR UTLX 12524 WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM A HOLE IN THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TANK.  THE IMMEDIATE AREA AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED. MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TRAINING INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A HOLE APPROXIMATELY THE DIAMETER OF A DIME IN THE UPPER PORTION OF THE TANK SHELL ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR AND ABOUT 1 FOOT FROM THE SIDE LADDER ON THE "A" END SIDE OF THE LADDER.  THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL PLUGGED THE HOLE WITH EPOXY PUTTY AND THE LEAK SUBSIDED.  THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO AN ISOLATED SIDING FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND PRODUCT TRANSFER.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS FOUND POOLED ON THE GROUND.  THIS WAS NEUTRALIZED.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE SHIPPER TOOK RESPONSIBILITY TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED CAR.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO EAGX 19025 ON 05/15/2002.

ON MAY 8, 2002, WHILE PREPARING TO UNLOAD RMGX 500, A LOADED GONDOLA CAR OF CONTAINERS OF CALCIUM CARBIDE, US PIPR AND FOUNDRY PERSONNEL FOUND THAT THE CONTAINERS OF CALCIUM CARBIDE HAD SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT AND THAT FIVE CONTAINERS HAD RIPPED AND SPILLED SOME OF THEIR CONTENTS.  LESS THAN 10 POUNDS OF LOSS WAS REPORTED AND ALL PRODUCT REMAINED INSIDE THE GONDOLA CAR.  THE CONTAINERS ARE REPORTED TO BE ROLL OVER BOTTLES-INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS-PER CODE IB4 IN 49CFR172.102.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED TO THE CONSIGNEE FACILITY AND ASSISTED PLANT PERSONNEL IN THE CLEANUP OF THE GONDOLA CAR AND REMOVAL OF THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS.  THE CAR WAS CLEANED AND THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED WITHOUT INCIDENT.
column172: Rail hopper car for solid materials only

column168: ETCX 29107 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT FROM THE MAGNETIC GAUGING DEVICE TUBE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE GAUGING DEVICE TUBE HAS A PIN HOLE LEAK.  THE INTERNAL TANK PRESSURE WAS 18 LBS.  EASTMAN CHEMICAL CO. HIRED A CONTRACTOR TO PLUG AND SECURE THE GAUGING DEVICE TUBE. AN APPROVAL TO MOVE A NON-CONFORMING TANK CAR WAS OBTAINED BY EASTMAN CHEMICAL CO. OF LONGVIEW, TX.  CHEMTREC REPORT # 05082002 079, OPR EVANS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: A CITIZEN LIVING NEAR THE RAILROAD REPORTED TO THE MOSSY HEAD FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT THEY WERE SMELLING A BAD ODOR FROM ONE OF THE RAIL CARS THAT WAS LOCATED IN FRONT OF THERE HOUSE AROUND 1120, 05/10/02.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT INVESTIGATED AND SAID THE ODOR WAS FROM ONE OF THE SIX CARS BUT WAS NOT ABLE TO DETECT WHICH ONE.  NOT KNOWING THE TYPE OF ODOR THEY CLOSED THE HIGHWAY, (HIGHWAY 90), AND EVACUATED 5 HOMES IN THE PROXIMITY OF THE CAR.  OUR MECHANICAL FOREMAN ARRIVED ON SCENE AND WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE WHICH CAR WAS LEAKING AND CONTACTED ME BY CELL PHONE.  AT 1300 EVACUATION WAS LIFTED AFTER TALKING WITH FIRE DEPARTMENT.  I ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 1330 AND FOUND THE CAR VENTING.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS DETERIORATED, THE VAPOR VALVE WAS LOOSE AT THE BASE OF THE VALVE, THE VAPOR PLUG WAS 2 TURNS LOOSE, AND THE VACUUM BREAKER GASKET WAS DEFECTIVE.  I INSTALLED A NEW GASKET ON THE MANWAY AND VACUUM BREAKER AND SECURED THE VAPOR VALVE AND PLUG WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS RINSED OFF WITH A BLEACH SOLUTION AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT 1432, 05-10-02.  NARRI SCORE: 240 5*(5+3+0)*(2+4)  CAUSE CODE: 209

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON MONDAY, MAY 13, 2002, AT APPROXIMATELY 4:15 PM, TANK CAR UTLX 11189, A LOADED CAR OF SULFURIC ACID, WAS BEING SWITCHED BY CSXT PERSONNEL IN THE CSXT SKILLMAN YARD IN HAWESVILLE, KENTUCKY.  DURING SWITCHING, PRODUCT SPLASHED THE TOP OF THE CAR ONTO A SWITCHMAN.  THE SWITCHMAN QUICKLY WASHED THE PRODUCT OFF, AND DECLINED MEDICAL ATTENTION AT THE TIME.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED ON MAY 15 AND FOUND THE LOADING HATCH BOLTS IMPROPERLY TORQUED AND THE HATCH GASKET MISALIGNED.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE HATCH BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE CSXT SWITCHMAN, AFTER THE END OF HIS SHIFT, FELT A BURNING SENSATION ON HIS FACE, NECK, AND HEAD, AND VISITED HIS PERSONAL PHYSICIAN.  THE SWITCHMAN WAS PRESCRIBED MEDICATION FOR SKIN BURNS AND RETURNED TO WORK ON HIS NEXT SCHEDULED SHIFT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Liner
column168: CREW UNLOADING TRAILERS OPENED A SHUTTLE TRUCK AND NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT FOUND ON ITS SIDE, LOCATED AT THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  THE VEHICLE WAS PULLED AWAY FROM THE LOADING AREA TO ISOLATE AND CONTAIN THE SHIPMENT.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CONTENTS OF ONE OF THE STEEL DRUMS HAD LEAKED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TWO DRUMS SHRINK WRAPPED TOGETHER AND PLACED ON A PALLET.  ONE OF THE CONTAINERS HAD LEAKED AT THE PLASTIC CLOSURE OF THE INNER LINER.  THE CONTENTS HAD EVAPORATED AND THE SMALL QUANTITY OF LIQUID WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND PLACED IN A HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED PIECE.  IT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD PENDING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS IN A SECURED AREA.
column172: Plastic receptacle within a protective steel drum

column14: 10 MILES W OF ODESSA AT CO. RD
column168: DRIVER/OPERATOR WAS TURNING NORTH ONTO COUNTY ROAD 866 FROM THE I-20 SERVICE ROAD WHEN THE TRACTOR/CARGO TANK BELLY LINE SUPPORT CHAIN FAILED ALLOWING THE BELLY HOSE TO BECOME STRESSED AND EXPERIENCE A SMALL TEAR. NINE GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ROADWAY.  LOCAL DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT AND CLEANUP ACTIONS TAKEN.  NO FURTHER ACTIONS WERE REQUESTED.  COMBINATION OF HEAVIER DUTY SUPPORT CHAIN AND/OR DRIVER INSPECTION OF EQUIPMENT WILL BE IMPLEMENTED TO AVOID REOCCURRENCE.

CURRENTLY AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER OF WHETHER TO DISPOSE OF OR RETURN TO SHIPPER.
THIS MERCHANDISE WAS LOADED IN THE TRAILER FROM DALLAS TO DOTHAN AND THE MERCHANDISE WAS DAMAGED WHEN UNLOADED AT DOTHAN DOCK........DAMAGED MERCHANDISE HAS BEEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHEN GOING ACROSS THE DOCK, A DOCKWORKER OBSERVED A DRUM THAT WAS STAGED ON THE DOCK THAT WAS SLIGHTLY LEAKING.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM WAS STAGED ON THE DOCK ON TOP OF A NAIL THAT WAS LYING ON THE FLOOR.  THE NAIL APPARENTLY WAS IN THE RIGHT POSITION TO PUNCTURE THE DRUM WHEN IT WAS PLACED ON TOP OF IT.  DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY FLIPPED OVER AND REPAIRED WITH DRUM PUTTY AND THEN PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER.  SPILLED MATERIAL EVAPORATED FROM THE CONCRETE FLOOR BEFORE ANY ACTION COULD BE TAKED TO MITIGATE.  SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

WHEN LOADING A BUNDLE OF STEEL INTO THE TRAILER DOCKWORKER RUBBED THE STEEL BUNDLE AGAINST THE DRUM SUBSEQUENTLY PUTTING A SMALL HOLE IN IT.  THE DRUM WAS LAID ON ITS SIDE AND REPAIRED WITH DRUM PUTTY AND THE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER ALONG WITH ABSORBENT USED TO CLEAN AND CONTAIN THE SPILL.  MORE THAN LIKELY COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF DUNNAGE OF SOME SORT HAD BEEN PLACED BETWEEN THE STEEL AND THE DRUM.  DRUM WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

SINCE HE WAS SO CLOSE TO HIS HOME TERMINAL HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO RETURN.  UPON RETURNING HIS TRAILER WAS STRIPPED AND A DRUM WAS DISCOVERED THAT HAD BEEN LOCATED ONTO A NAIL WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY PUNCTURED THE DRUM AT THE BOTTOM SEAM.  DRUM WAS REPAIRED WITH DRUM PUTTY AND PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.  SPILLED MATERIAL BASICALLY EVAPORATED BEFORE ANY MITIGATION ACTION COULD BE TAKEN.

column168: WHILE IN TRANSIT DRIVER OF VEHICLE HAD TO SLAM ON BRAKES TO AVOID SUDDEN MOVEMENT OF ANOTHER VEHICLE.  BY DOING SO A BUNDLE OF STEEL THAT WAS IN THE TRAILER SLIGHTLY SLID FORWARD AND PUNCTURED A DRUM THAT WAS IN FRONT OF THE BUNDLE OF STEEL.  DRIVER DID HAVE A PALLET INBETWEEN THE TWO SHIPMENTS TO PROTECT THE DRUM BUT THE BUNDLE OF STEEL PUNCTURE THE PROTECTIVE PALLET ALSO.  AFTER AVOIDING COLLISION WITH OTHER VEHICLE DRIVER PULLED OVER TO INSPECT LOAD AND FOUND THE LEAKING DRUM.  DRIVER USED HIS ON BOARD VEHICLE SPILL KIT TO ABSORB AND CONTAIN SPILLED MATERIAL AND USED DRUM PUTTY TO TEMPORARILY REPAIR AND STOP LEAKING DRUM.  DRIVER RETURNED TO YARD WHERE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP AND DAMAGE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

WHILE AT ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE DRIVER SAW ANOTHER DRUM THERE THAT LOOKED SIMILAR TO THE DRUM HE JUST RECOVERED. CONSIGNEE INFORMED OUR DRIVER THAT THE BUILDING MIGHT BE CAUSED BECAUSE INNER PRODUCT IS HOT WHEN POURED INTO CONTAINER WHEN MANUFACTURED AND SOMETIME THIS WAS THE RESULT IF TOO HOT.

WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM TRAILER DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED ONE INTACT PALLET THAT HAD SOME WET BOXES UNDER THE STRETCHWRAP IT WAS WRAPPED IN. THEY OPENED THE WET BOXES AND IN ONE OF THEM FOUND A PLASTIC JUG THAT WAS PARTIALLY CRUSHED AT THE HANDLE WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY CAUSED THE LEAK. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE. WE NEVER DETERMINED THE CAUSE OF THE DAMAGED BOTTLE INSIDE THE UNDAMAGED BOX.

AS THE DRIVER WAS INSPECTING  HIS VEHICLE, HE NOTICED LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER. HE CALLED DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC. SAFETY DEPARTMENT TO REPORT THE LEAK. THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT CALLED ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND THEY DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE. THE LEAKING DRUMS WAS IDENTIFIED AND PLACED IN AN "OVERPACK" DRUM. THE LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS PICKED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS, WHICH WERE ALSO PLACED IN THE "OVERPACK" DRUM. THE TRUCK THEN DELIVERED THE LOAD, WHICH INCLUDED THE "OVERPACK" DRUM, TO THE CONSIGNEE.

ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED DOWN ON THE FLOOR TO CONTAIN ALL LIQUIDS. LATER THAT EVENING AN ENVIRONMENTAL TEAM WAS CALLED CLEAN THE TRAILER FLOOR SO THAT IT COULD BE PLACED BACK INTO SERVICE. THE OVERPACK CONTAINER AND THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS ALL SAVED BY CF IN AN ATTEMPT TO RETURN THEM TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER.

CF PERSONNEL FOUND A CRUSHED CONTAINER THAT CONTAINED SODIUM HYDROXIDE THAT WAS CRUSHED WHILE UNLOADING THE TRUCK. THE MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED INTO A DRUM LINER AND THEN INTO A 14 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. THE BOX WAS ALSO PLACED INTO THE SAME DRUM. NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED. THE REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER WAS CONTACTED. MR. TUCKER CONTACTED MR. HARVEY DIRECTLY AFTER THE SPILL WAS REPORTED. ALL WASTE WILL BE SENT THROUGH THE FACILITIES LOCAL CHANNELS.

column168: 43. VALVE OPEN PLUGS REMOVED  THE SOUTHWEST PENNSYLVANIA RAILROAD IS STORING 215 RESIDUE EMPTY TANK CARS FOR BP PRODUCTS NORTH AMERICA [LAST CONTAINED LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS (ISOBUTANE), CLASS 2.1, UN 1075].  THE SWP-1 TRAIN CREW WAS TRAVELING NORTH BY THE STORAGE AREA IN YOUNGWOOD, PENNSYLVANIA WHEN THE CREW NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD JUST ABOVE THE RAIL.  THE CREW REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE VPO WHO INSTRUCTED THEM TO MOVE THEIR TRAIN BEYOND THE SAFE MINIMUM EVACUATION DISTANCE AS IDENTIFIED IN THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK.  THE VPO THEN CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL CLOSED STATE ROUTE 119 AND EVACUATED 5 RESIDENCES (6-PERSONS-5 ADULTS AND 1 TEENAGER).  THE VPO CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FOUND THE LIQUID AND VAPOR LINES TO BE OPEN AND THE PLUGS REMOVED.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AT 4:04 A.M. THERE WAS NO PROPERTY DAMAGE OR PERSONAL INJURY.  THE FBI AND THE PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE CONDUCTED A CRIMINAL INVESTIGATION WITH CONCERNS OF TAMPERING (VANDALISM).  FIVE OF THE CARS COUPLED TO THE LEAKING CAR WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND IN THE SAME CONDITION (VALVES OPEN PLUGS REMOVED).  THEIR INVESTIGATION WAS INCONCLUSIVE AND CLOSED AS UNFOUNDED.  IN ADDITION, 180 TANK CARS AT VARIOUS LOCATIONS WERE INSPECTED WITH EIGHT HAVING DISCREPANCIES.  ALL DISCREPANCIES HAVE BEEN CORRECTED.

(18:45) - WAS NOTIFIED BY DALE STEVENS OF A POSSIBLE HAZMAT SPILL. (18:50) - DETERMINED WHAT IT WAS.  CHECKED THE ERG AND BY THE INFORMATION THAT I GATHERED I HAD THE LOWER END OF THE DOCK ISOLATED, AT LEAST 200 METERS AND CONTACTED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AT THE GENERAL OFFICE. (18:55) - I WAS PUT IN CONTACT WITH EDDIE YANCE.  I EXPLAINED THE CIRCUMSTANCES TO HIM. WHILE UNLOADING A STORAGE TRAILER, DALE PULLED OUT A SKID AND NOTICED A WET SPOT ON THE FLOOR.  HE THEN INSPECTED THE SKID WHILE IT WAS ON THE FLOOR AND SEEN THE LEAKING BOX.  AT THIS TIME HE CALLED ME ON THE RADIO.  MR. VANCE GAVE THESE DIRECTIONS TO ME. #1, PUT ON PROTECTIVE HAZMAT GEAR, UNSTACKED THE SKID, OPENED THE DAMAGED BOX AND DETERMINED THE EXTENT OF THE LEAK, RECOUPED THE BOX WITH THE GOOD PRODUCT IN IT AND PUT THIS OUR FOR DELIVERY IN THE MORNING.  PUT DAMAGED PORTION IN HAZMAT CONTAINER UNTIL DISPOSITION IN RECEIVED.  I FOLLOWED THESE INSTRUCTIONS.  I FOUND OUT THAT ALL THAT WAS NEEDED WAS THE CAPS TO BE RETIGHTENED.

WHILE LOADING CARGO TANK FROM FRAC TANK, CARGO TANK WAS OVERFILLED ALLOWING 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO LEAK OUT.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE PAVEMENT AREA.  THE TANK WAS NOT VISUALLY CHECKED THROUGH THE TOP OPENING DURING THE LOADING PROCESS.  THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOADED WAS BEING GAUGED BY THE TIMING METHOD.  ALSO, THE SAFETY OVERFILL PROBE WAS NOT INSTALLED ON THE TRUCK.  FUTURE LOADS WILL BE VISUALLY CHECKED THROUGH THE TOP DOME DURING THE LOADING PROCESS FOR CAPACITY AND THE SAFETY OVERFILL PROBE WILL BE INSTALLED PRIOR TO THE COMMENCEMENT OF THE LOADING PROCESS.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE EXIT 47 PLAZA, THE VICKERY TRANSPORTATION,  INC. DRIVER HEARD A LOUD NOISE.  AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT, APPROXIMATELY THIRTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY, THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE SHIPPER NOT PROPERLY IDENTIFYING THE PRODUCT.  AS A RESULT OF THE IMPROPER PRODUCT IDENTIFICATION, THE PRODUCT REACTED WITH THE RUBBER LINING OF THE TRAILER.  IT HAD INITIALLY BEEN REPORTED THAT A FIRE OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT, HOWEVER, IT WAS THE REDDISH ORANGE GLOW OF THE FUMING NITRIC ACID VAPOR THAT GAVE THE APPEARANCE OF A FIRE.  HEPACO, INC. AND HULCHER SERVICES, INC. OF MEMPHIS, TENNESSEE PERFORMED THE CLEANUP.  THE FREE PRODUCT AND AFFECTED SOIL WERE NEUTRALIZED WITH PORTLAND CEMENT.  THE AFFECTED AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH A PRESSURE WASHER,  APPROXIMATELY 3895 GALLONS OF WASH WATER AND 660 YARDS OF CLEANUP DEBRIS AND NEUTRALIZED SOIL WERE GENERATED DURING THE DECONTAMINATION PROCESS.  THE WASH WATER WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE VICKERY ENVIRONMENTAL. INC. FACILITY IN VICKERY, OHIO FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CLEANUP DEBRIS AND NEUTRALIZED SOIL WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC., FACILITY IN EMELLE, ALABAMA FOR DISPOSAL.  AT THIS TIME THERE ARE NO CONFIRMED REPORTS OF INDIVIDUALS SEEKING MEDICAL ATTENTION OR REQUIRING HOSPITALIZATION AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON MAY 26, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 08:00 A.M. AT THE INTERSECTION OF PADDOCK & SEYMOUR AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  OUR DRIVER WAS SOUTHBOUND ON PADDOCK RD. IN THE RIGHT LANE.  ANOTHER VEHICLE WAS FOLLOWING IN THE RIGHT LANE ALSO.  OUR DRIVER WENT TO MAKE A RIGHT TURN.  HE STRADDLED THE LEFT AND RIGHT LANES IN ORDER TO MAKE THE RIGHT TURN.  THE OTHER VEHICLE ASSUMED THE TRUCK WAS GOING TO TURN LEFT AND SHE IMMEDIATELY STARTED TO THE RIGHT.  THE TRUCK THEN STARTED TURNING TO THE RIGHT AND CAUGHT HER IN A RIGHT HAND SQUEEZE.  THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS AT THE LOADING HEADS OF THE TRAILER WHEN THE IMPACT OCCURRED.  OUR DRIVER STOPPED AND REALIZED THE LOADING HEADS OF THE TRAILER WERE LEAKING AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES.  USENERGY SYSTEMS, INC. - ENVIRONMENTAL DIVISION RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT.  APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED.  THE CINCINNATI FIRE DEPARTMENT APPLIED FIRE RETARDANT FOAM. US ENERGY CONSTRUCTED TWO UNDERFLOW DAMS TO PREVENT FURTHER MIGRATION OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL.  A DRUM-VACUUM WAS USED TO COLLECT 300 GALLONS OF PETROLEUM-IMPACTED WATER.  THE WATER WAS TRANSPORTED TO USENERGY SHELBYVILLE, KY FACILITY FOR PROCESSING.  USENERGY EXCAVATED THE PETROLEUM IMPACTED SOIL.  APPROXIMATELY 108.47 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WERE REMOVED AND TRANSPORTED TO WASTE MANAGEMENTS STONY HOLLOW FACILITY IN DAYTON, OH FOR DISPOSAL.

AFTER INITIAL INSPECTION BY NS TRAINMASTER, RESPONSE CONTRACTOR H.M.H.T.T.C., CONSHOHOCKEN, PA, WAS REQUESTED BY THE SHIPPER TO RESPOND.  CONTRACTOR REPORTED LIQUID LEAK ORIGINATING FROM SAFETY VALVE DUE TO TANK CAR BEING OVERLOADED.  LIQUID LEVEL WAS NOTED TO BE AT THE TOP OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE. APPROXIMATELY 450-500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF INTO 10 X 55 GALLON DRUMS.  CAR WAS RESECURED BY CONTRACTOR AND OKAYED FOR FORWARDING TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION.  NOTE: CAR WAS DELIVERED BY CST TO NS WEST FALLS YARD AND CR LOCAL DELIVERY TRACK ON APPROXIMATELY 5/20/02.

ON THE EVENING OF MAY 28, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:15 P.M., A DIESEL FUEL SPILL OCCURRED ON THE PROPERLY OF RIVERTON TRUCKERS, INC.  THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS A VALVE BEING BROKEN OFF A FUEL TANKER TRUCK AFTER THE OPERATOR OF THE FUEL STRUCK THE BUMPER OF A PARKED DUMP-TRUCK WHILE TURNING A CORNER IN THE FUEL TRUCK.  AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF DIESEL FUEL LEAKED UPON THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT BY THE TIME THE MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL WERE ABLE TO CLOSE THE VALVE TO STOP THE FLOW.  THE RIVERTON SAFETY DIRECTOR WAS ON THE PREMISES AT THE TIME AND TOOK CHARGE OF CONTAINING THE SPILL WITH LONG ABSORBENT BAGS.  SHOP PERSONNEL SPREAD OIL DRY ABSORBENT ON THE FUEL THAT HAD COLLECTED ON POOLS IN THE VICINITY OF THE FUEL TRUCK.  VARIOUS PERSONNEL WORKED ON THE CONTAINMENT OF THE SPILL FOR APPROXIMATELY FOUR (4) HOURS, UNTIL THE SAFETY DIRECTOR WAS SATISFIED THAT ALL THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THESE MEASURES EFFECTIVELY CONTAINED THE DIESEL FUEL FROM RUNNING OFF THE PROPERTY.  A NEIGHBOR IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO THE RIVERTON TERMINAL BEGAN PULLING ON AND OFF THE RIVERTON LOT IN HIS PERSONAL VEHICLE AND CIRCLING THE BUILDING.  AFTER THE THIRD TIME HE CIRCLED THE BUILDING, THE SAFETY DIRECTOR INSTRUCTED THE STOP PERSONNEL TO CLOSE AND LOCK THE GATE, BECAUSE HE DID NOT KNOW THE IDENTITY OR INTENTION OF THE PERSON CIRCLING THE BUILDING.  NOT LONG THEREAFTER, THE NEIGHBOR RETURNED WITH PERSONNEL FROM THE HEALTH DEPARTMENT AND SELLERSBURG FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE GATE WAS UNLOCKED TO ALLOW THE INDIVIDUALS FROM THE HEALTH DEPT. AND FIRE DEPT. ONTO THE LOT.  BY THIS TIME THE FUEL SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE SAFETY DIRECTOR HAD CONTACTED ME, IN ORDER TO COME TO RIVERTON TO SPEAK TO THE REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE TWO AGENCIES.  I INQUIRED OF THE SAFETY DIRECTOR IF ANY AGENCIES HAD BEEN CALLED TO REPORT THE SPILL AND HE ANSWERED THAT THEY HADN'T BECAUSE HE THOUGHT AS LONG AS THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON OUR PROPERTY THAT WE WOULD HANDLE IT INTERNALLY BY CLEANING IT, THEN CALL AN ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCY TO HAL OFF THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL IN THE DAYLIGHT. UPON MY ARRIVAL AT RIVERTON AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 A.M., I MET WITH KATHERINE TAYLOR OF CLARK COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT. SHE INFORMED ME THAT DUE TO THE VOLUME OF THE SPILL, THAT I NEEDED TO CONTACT AN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED DIESEL FUEL AND TO CHECK THE LOCAL CREEK TO INSURE NO FUEL MADE IT THERE, THUS CONTAMINATING IT. SHE SAID THIS NEEDED TO BE DONE; SO CLEAN UP COULD BEGIN AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. I ASKED IF I NEEDED TO MAKE ANY CALLS TO OTHER AGENCIES AND WAS TOLD THAT SHE HAD ALREADY CONTACTED IDEM AND THAT THEY MAY RESPOND OR CALL BUT A PRESENT THERE WERE NO OTHER CONTACTS THAT HAD TO BE MADE. I IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED JIM BURRIER OF MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. HE ARRIVED AT THE RIVERTON TERMINAL AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 A.M. IN THE MEANTIME, I ALONG WITH MS. TAYLOR RAN NUMBERS ON GALLONS OF FUEL THAT POSSIBLY COULD HAVE SPILLED.BASICALLY, I DEDUCTED THE AMOUNTS OF FUEL THAT WAS PUT IN THE TRUCKS ON THE L

column168: DRIVER WAS ENROUTE FROM WILMINGTON, DE TO FALLS, PA TO DELIVER A LOAD OF RECYCLED FUEL OIL. DRIVER FAILED TO MAKE A TURN ON EAST FALLS ROAD ONTO A BRIDGE OVER BUTTERMILK CREEK. THE TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT TURNED OVER ONTO THE DRIVER'S SIDE AND PART OF THE TRACTOR PUNCTURED OVER ONTO THE DRIVER'S SIDE AND PART OF THE TRACTOR PUNCTURED THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER, CAUSING A SPILL OF PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT RAN OVER THE BRIDGE RAIL INTO THE CREEK AND ALONG THE CREEK BANK ON THE SOUTH SIDE. THE CREEK EMPTIES INTO THE SUSQUEHANNA RIVER A SHORT DISTANCE DOWNSTREAM. RAPID STREAM FLOW CARRIED SOME OF THE PRODUCT INTO THE SUSQUEHANNA ALMOST IMMEDIATELY. WITNESSES CALLED LOCAL AUTHORITIES, WHO ALSO CONTACTED THE PA STATE POLICE AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, STATE POLICE NOTIFIED OUR WILMINGTON PA STATE POLICE NOTIFIED OUR WILMINGTON FACILITY A SHORT TIME LATER. TEEM ENVIRONMENTAL,THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO PLACE BOOMS AND ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN AND RECOVER SPILLED MATERIAL. THE CLEANUP EFFORTS HAVE CONTINUED THROUGH 2003 IN COOPERATION WITH THE PADEP. THE DRIVER BRIEFLY LOST CONSCIOUSNESS, WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE TYLER HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION, AND WAS RELEASED WITHIN A COUPLE HOURS. PA STATE POLICE INSPECTED THE TRACTOR/TRAILER AND DID NOT FIND ANY EQUIPMENT MALFUNCTION. THE DRIVER WAS CHARGED BY THE PA STATE POLICE WITH CARELESS DRIVING, IMPROPER LANE MOVEMENT, AND UNSAFE SPEED. THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED FROM HIS EMPLOYMENT DUE TO THE INCIDENT. OTHER COMPANY DRIVERS WERE GIVEN SUPPLEMENTARY TRAINING OF SAFE DRIVING PRACTICES. WE BELIEVE THIS INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF THIS INDIVIDUAL DRIVER'S UNSAFE DRIVING ON THIS DATE AND THAT IT IS NOT LIKELY TO REOCCUR.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS THAT LED TO THE INCIDENT:  THE TRACTOR-TANKER CAUGHT FIRE, WHEN AN EXPLOSION AND FIRE OCCURRED DUE TO UNKNOWN CAUSES, WHEN 87 OCTANE 9.0 RVP UNLEADED GASOLINE WAS BIENG PUMPED OUT OF AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK TO SWITCH FUEL, FUEL BEING MORE PARTICULARLY DESCRIBED AS 87 OCTANE 9.0 RVP UNLEADED GASOLINE, WHICH DOES NOT MEET FUEL SPECS OF ATLANTA FUEL CONTROL AREA OF DAVIDSON COUNTY, LEXINGTON, NORTH CAROLINA.  THE CORRECT FUEL FOR THIS AREA EFFECTIVE JUNE 1, 2002 WAS 87 OCTANE 7.8 RVP, THIS BEING THE REASON THAT THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED, BECAUSE 9.0 RVP SPEC WAS IN THE TANK.  ACTION TAKEN AT TIME FIRE DISCOVERED:(2) MEN SHUT OFF/CUT OFF ALL VALVES AND COUPLINGS AND EVACUATED THE SITE.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS:  TO BE MORE FAMILIAR WITH THE COUNTIES IN NORTH CAROLINA THAT REQUIRE 7.8 RVP SPEC PRODUCT EFFECTIVE THE 1ST DAY OF JUNE OF EACH YEAR.

FIVE CASES OF PRODUCT WERE FOUND ON THE CARRIER'S DOCK, DAMAGED.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE CASES, IT WAS DETERMINED THE FORKS OF A FORKLIFT CAUSED THE DAMAGE TO THE CASES.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT, WHICH WAS CLEANED BY THE DOCK WORKERS.  THE DAMAGED CASES WERE PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE REST OF THE FREIGHT WAS SHIPPED TO CONSIGNEE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

UPON UNLOADING THE TRAILER, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE PALLET WAS WET BENEATH THE FREIGHT.  SINCE IT WAS LABELED AS POISONOUS, THE LOADER CALLED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WHO INSTRUCTED A RESPONSE CREW TO REMOVE THE PAIL AND OVERPACK IT.  IT WAS LEARNED THAT THE PAIL CONTAINED CEMENT CRACK SEALER.  THE PAIL APPARENTLY HAD A PACKAGE FAILURE ON BOTTOM SEAM.  THERE WERE NO FURTHER INCIDENTS REGARDING THIS FREIGHT.

DURING AN EARLY MORNING LOADING AT A REMOTE REFINED PRODUCT DISTRIBUTION PLAN (YELLOW CREEK GAS PLANT RUN BY DUKE ENERGY) THE VEHICLE DRIVER LEFT THE OPERATION UNATTENDED.  UPON RETURNING HE NOTED SOME FUEL RUNNING OVER THE SIDE OF THE TANK.  THE LOADING OPERATION WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED.  THE DRIVER ESTIMATED ONLY A FEW GALLONS HAD BEEN LOST, AND LEFT THE LOADING AREA.  WHEN THE GAS PLANT DAY SHIFT ARRIVED AND NOTED THE FUEL ON THE GROUND, THEY NOTIFIED FLYING J WHO IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED BOTH THEIR CONTRACT AND PLANT EMERGENCY RESPONSE GROUPS TO THE SCENE.  THE FUEL WAS ON THE GROUND AND SPREADING SLOWLY TOWARD A SMALL RUNOFF FED DITCH THAT FLOWS THROUGH OPEN FIELDS OVER A THOUSAND YARDS TO A CREEK.  A SMALL UNDERFLOW DAM WITH ABSORBENT BOOM WAS PLACED IN THE DITCH TO PROTECT THE DITCH AND PREVENT FUEL FROM SPREADING.  THE CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE EXCAVATED, CLEAN FILL WAS PLACED IN THE EXCAVATION AND THE AREA RETURNED TO NORMAL.  THE INCIDENT WAS THE SUBJECT OF THE NEXT DRIVER'S SAFETY MEETING WHERE THE REQUIREMENTS FOR UNINTERRUPTED ATTENDANCE DURING ALL LOADING AND UNLOADING OPERATIONS WAS STRESSED.  THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED.

column168: FILE: 2209-D  SHIPPER ASTI AWB#YYZ 4011365147 CMI ON 05/07/2002 AT 02:15 A CALL CAME IN THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE LEAKING IN THE CANADIAN CAGE IN BUILDING "B" AT OUR SPORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED T 145 HUNTER DRIVE WILMINGTON OHIO 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS CAROLYN FRYE AND TERRY RUGERRIE RESPONDED TO INVESTIGATE THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION. UPON ARRIVAL THE SPILL TECHNICIANS OBSERVED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND FOUND THAT IT WAS WET ON THE OUTSIDE AND FOLLOWING STANDARD SAFETY PROCEDURES PH'D THE WET PORTION ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE WHICH INDICATED THAT THE CONTENTS MAY BE A REGULATED CORROSIVE MATERIAL. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND OPENED THE PACKAGE TO DETERMINE WHAT WAS INSIDE THAT WAS LEAKING. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS FOUND A 1 X 1 GALLON PLASTIC RECEPTACLE THAT WAS LABELED "CORROSIVE" AND HAD THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME, HAZARD CLASS UN NUMBER AS INDICATED IN SECTION IV. 12 THRU 13 OF THIS REPORT. THE CLOSURE ON THE 1 GALLON PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED IT TO LEAK. THERE WASN'T ANY ABSORBANT MATERIAL USED ONLY SHREDDED PAPER STRIPS WHICH DID NOT ABSORB THE LEAKING PRODUCT. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS PLACED THE SHIPMENT INTO TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH AN ABSORBANT PAD AND FURTHER OVERPACKED IT INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITY AND PLACED INTO OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCAL AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. CLEAR OF SCENE 02:52

THE AREA WAS EVACUATED UNTIL IT WAS RENDERED SAFE UPON ARRIVAL THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND USING A PHOTO IONIZING DETECTOR THEY BEGAN SEARCHING THROUGH PACKAGES TO DETERMINE WHICH PACKAGE WAS EMITTING THE ODOR. THE ALARM ON THE DETECTOR ALARMED WHEN THEY PLACED IT UP TO THE ABOVE SHIPMENT AND IT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED AND REMOVED FROM THE AREA. UPON EXAMINING THE OUTER PACKAGE THERE WEREN'T ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THAT THERE WERE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSIDE SO THEY OPEN THE BOX AND FOUND A 1 X 1 QUART  METAL CAN HAD LEAKED DUE TO THE LID ON THE METAL PAINT CAN NOT BEING SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS ALSO IN THE BOX WERE 5 SMALL. WOODEN TABLES AND ANOTHER SMALL BOX OF MISCELLANEOUS NON-HAZARDOUS/NON REGULATED ITEMS. THE MANUFACTURES WARNING LABEL ON THE 1 QUART  METAL CAN STATED: WARNING EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION STEEL 1A1 DRUM AND PLACED IT IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITIES SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

CONWAY EMPLOYEE DERRICK SMITH WAS REMOVING FREIGHT FROM A PICK-UP DELIVERY TRAILER WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  WHILE MOVING FREIGHT, HIS FORKLIFT BLADES PUNCTURED THE SKID CAUSING A HOLE TO FORM IN THE BOTTOM OF THE SKID WHICH CONTAINED 40 BAGS STACKED, WITH SHRINK WRAP AROUND THE SIDES.  ONCE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED A SUPERVISOR, WHO AT WHICH TIME REMOVED ALL EMPLOYEES FROM THE TRAILER AND CALLED CHEMTREC FOR FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE PUNCTURED BAG WAS REMOVED FROM THE SKID AND PLACED INTO A SEAL SALVAGE DRUM AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.  AS A CONSEQUENCE OF THE INCIDENT, FORKLIFT AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HANDLING RE-TRAINING HAS TAKEN PLACE TO ENSURE PROPER CARE IS FURTHER FOLLOWED TO PREVENT THE INCIDENT FROM OCCURRING AGAIN.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AROUND THE INNER CLOSURE AREA DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS LATER CONTACTED REGARDING DISPOSITION.

JAMES RIOUX, OUR DRIVER HAD HOOKED UP LINES AND FITTINGS.  OPERATORS AT ENTERGY GAVE OK TO OPEN LINES WHEN HE NOTICED A LEAK AT MULE VALVE ON ENTERGY INTAKE VALVE.  THEY RELEASED PRESSURE ON THE LINES AND THEN USED ANOTHER 2" DOUBLE FEMALE FITTING AND HOOKED UP LINES AGAIN AND STARTED TO UNLOAD AGAIN.  OUR DRIVER OPENED THE LINES AND IN THE SAME AREA ON MALE INTAKE STARTED LEAKING AGAIN.  OUR DRIVER CLOSED THE LINES AND ATTEMPTED TO CRACK THE LINE TO RELEASE PRESSURE AND PRODUCT SPRAYED FROM FITTING.  A WORKER PASSED BY AND OUR DRIVER ASKED HIM FOR HELP.  HE ASKED HIM TO HAND HIM THE WATER HOSE THAT WAS NEXT TO OUR DRIVER.  OUR DRIVER LOOKED OVER HIS SHOULDER WAITING FOR HIM TO COME AROUND BEHIND HIM TO GRAB THE WATER HOSE WHEN HE SAW THE WORKER REACH WITH HIS BARE HANDS AND TRY TO RETURN THE HOSE FITTING EARS TO THE CLOSED POSITION.  THE WORKER WAS SPRAYED WITH ACID ON HIS LEFT ARM AND HAND.

column168: TANK CAR PLMX 30061 WAS FOUND LEAKING WHILE IN THE CSXT SIBERT YARD IN MOBILE, AL.  ICING WAS OBSERVED AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING BY A CSXT YARD CREW.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT INSPECTED THE CAR AND STATED THAT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED AND THEY DEMOBILIZED FROM THE CSXT YARD AT 1545 HRS.  CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER - GLEASON ARRIVED AT THE CSXT YARD AT 1605 HRS. GLEASON CHECKED THE TANK CAR PRESSURE AND FOUND THE PRESSURE TO BE 275 PSIG.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1620 HRS THE TANK CAR BEGAN VENTING PRODUCT THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED BACK TO THE CSXT YARD.  EVACUATION OF THE CLASSIFICATION YARD AND TELEGRAPH ROAD (A PUBLIC ROAD) WAS COMMENCED AT 1650 HRS.  AT 1730 HRS THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SPRAYED THE TANK CAR WITH WATER IN AN ATTEMPT TO LOWER THE INTERNAL PRESSURE.  THE WATER SPRAYED LOWERED THE PRESSURE AS INTENDED AND NO FURTHER PRODUCT VENTING OCCURRED.  THE SHIPPER HAD OVERLOADED THE TANK CAR AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE EXCESS PRODUCT FROM THE CAR.  A TOTAL OF 3400 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM CAR, LEAVING AT OUTAGE OF 17 INCHES AND A PRESSURE OF 130 PSIG.  THE TANK CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN PASCAGOULA, MS.

HE REPLACED HE DEFECTIVE 75LB VALVE WITH A NEW 165 LB VALVE.  HE THEN STENCILED THE CAR TO SHOW THE NEW PRESSURE RATING AND AND THE NEW PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE TEST DATES.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND READY TO RETURN TO TRANSPORTATION AT 1330 HRS.

AT 15:23 HRS THE SPILL TEAM SUPERVISOR, BRUCE CUNNINGHAM, GAVE THE ALL CLEAR AND THE EMPLOYEES RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA.  3 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATORS, 3 PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS AND 1 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL SUPERVISOR WERE ON THE SCENE UNTIL THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND THE AREA CLEANED. ALSO THEY NOTED THAT THERE WASN'T ANY ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE CLOSURE DID NOT HAVE ANY POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THEM IN PLACE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION STEEL 1A1 DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.  NOTE SECTION VII. 35#, COLUMN C. SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO THE CAR AND, AFTER EXAMINATION, DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS FOLDED OR CRIMPED ON THE HINGE SIDE.  THE GASKET WAS REPOSITIONED AND THE MANWAY WAS RESECURED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED RICHARD CARMAN, SPECIAL AGENT, ADVISED AN ODOR WAS NOTICED FROM TANKCAR GATX 44015 LOCATED ON TRACK 205 IN THE NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD.  MR. SIMPSON STATED THE TANKCAR WAS INSPECTED AND ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS FOUND ONE THIRD OPEN.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE ODOR CEASED.  MR. SIMPSON FURTHER ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED AND CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

PAT, VICTORIA POLICE DEPARTMENT, REPORTED TANKCARS ON THE TRACKS NEAR THE BLOOMINGTON ELEMENTARY SCHOOL AT 200 LEONARD STREET WERE EMITTING AN ODOR. THE PRINCIPAL OF THE SCHOOL HAD NOTIFIED PERSONNEL IN THE YARD AND REQUESTED THE TANKCARS BE MOVED AWAY FROM THE SCHOOL.  A SHELTER HAD BEEN SET UP IN THE SCHOOL BECAUSE TEACHERS AND CHILDREN WERE COMPLAINING OF HEADACHES AND THROAT AND EYE IRRITATIONS.  EMS AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ON SCENE AT THE SCHOOL FOR TREATMENT.  MGR. CTS, FRANK LERCH WAS NOTIFIED AND HE ADVISED THAT MGR. CTS, MIKE KELLY WAS ENROUTE TO HANDLE THE INCIDENT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED PER MR. LERCH. MGR KELLY WAS CONFERRED WITH JOHN NICHOLS, FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT.  MR. NICHOLS REPORTED THE RAILCARS WERE ON THE TRACK APPROXIMATELY ONE HUNDRED FIFTY YARDS FROM THE SCHOOL BEFORE THEY WERE MOVED.  THE WINDS WERE BLOWING SOUTHEAST.  MGR KELLY ARRIVED ON SCENE AND WAS ADVISED BY MR. DENNIS WOOSTER WITH DOW CHEMICAL THAT HE HAD JUST INSPECTED THE ABOVE CAR AND FOUND THE PACKING NUT ON THE LIQUID VALVE WAS LOOSE ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE THE CAR.  MR. WOOSTER ADVISED THAT HE TIGHTENED THE NUT AND STOPPED THE VAPOR RELEASE.

DON SNOW, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED TANKCAR ACFX 88921 SLOSHED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF ITS LOAD ONTO THE FACE AND ARMS OF J.R. MOTTRAM, SWITCHMAN, WHO WENT TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL. SAM KEPHART, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, WAS ON SCENE AND HAD THE TANKCAR SET OUT IN THE YARD, PENDING MGR SNOW'S INSPECTION. DAVE STEEL, SACRAMENTO COUNTY HAZMAT ADVISED HE WOULD ALSO BE RESPONDING TO THE YARD. MGR SNOW'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS APPEARED TO BE LOOSE. HE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, ROMIC CHEMICAL AND THEY CONTRACTED WITH MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL TO REPLACE THE MANWAY GASKET AND RESECURE THE MANWAY BOLTS.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: DIRK HARDY, SENIOR MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED A LEAKING TANKCAR ON TRACK ONE IN THE NORTH PLATTE YARD. HE ADVISED KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND WAS ENROUTE. MR. HARDY REPORTED THE TANKCAR HAD A STEADY DRIP AT THE BOTTOM AND ADVISED HE WAS UNCERTAIN OF THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL RELEASED. MGR KEELING REPORTED THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A LOOSE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND ADVISED THE CAP WAS SECURED STOPPING THE LEAK. HE ADVISED THAT LESS THAN ONE QUART OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED AND HAD EVAPORATED BEFORE IT REACHED THE GROUND.

JIM, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISED THE LOCAL SWITCH CREW REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 643677 POSSIBLY LEAKING AT THE FOURTH STREET YARD IN LOS ANGELES, CA. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE 4TH STREET YARD. A SLIGHT VAPOR WAS NOTED FROM THE VACUUM BREAKER ON TOP OF THE MANWAY PLATE. MR. COOPER WAS ABLE TO CONTAIN THE VAPOR RELEASE BY BAGGING IT, TAPING IT AND MAKING A COCOON TO CONTAIN THE VAPOR UNTIL A REPLACEMENT VALVE COULD BE OBTAINED. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED, WHO MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH RUSCAR TO OVER NIGHT A REPLACEMENT VALVE. KURT BLODGETT, CLAIMS REPRESENTATIVE, ADVISED FOUR EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO THE GLENDALE MEMORIAL HOSPITAL FOR EXPOSURE TO THE VAPORS. THE FOLLOWING MORNING, MANAGER COPPER REMOVED THE VACUUM BREAKER AND REPLACED IT WITH A PIPE PLUG TO SECURE THE CAR. SHORTLY AFTER THE CAR WAS SECURED THE SWITCH CREW MOVED THE CAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS, AND NOTED THE CAR LEAKING AGAIN, MANAGER COOPER REINSPECTED THE CAR, OPENING THE MANWAY.  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISSING A TEMPORARY REPLACEMENT GASKET OF GOR-TEX WAS INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY SECURED. ON FRIDAY, MAY 24, 2002, REPRESENTATIVES OR RUSCAR REPLACED THE VACUUM BREAKER. CAR TO BE RELEASED ONCE FRA  MOVEMENT AUTHORITY IS RECEIVED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: CHARLIE BROOKER, STRANG YARDMASTER, REPORTED A TANKCAR POSSIBLY LEAKING DUE TO REPORT OF A STRONG ODOR SOMEWHERE IN THE BOWL OF THE STRANG YARD. DAYNA JONES, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONFERRED WITH GLENN THOMAS, DIRECTOR OF ENVIRONMENTAL OPERATIONS. MR. THOMAS CONTRACTED WITH EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT. DON JENKS, MANAGER OF COMPLIANCE MEASUREMENT, ALSO RESPONDED. MGR. JENKS REPORTED THAT NATX 29126 WAS FOUND IN THE YARD EMITTING ODOR FROM THE LIQUID LINE PLUG, WHICH WAS LOOSE. THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TANK CAR RETURNED TO SERVICE.

DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY REPORTED HE WOULD BE INVESTIGATING A STRONG SMELL OF AMMONIA IN THE TUCSON YARD AROUND TRACK 21. MGR. JOHNSON DISCOVERED A VAPOR LEAK COMING FROM THE PRESURE PLATE OF CAR GATX 18121. THE TANK CAR WAS SET OUT AND THE SHIPPER, FARMLAND INDUSTRIES, WAS CONTACTED. THE SHIPPER, BOB ITA, FARMLAND INDUSTRIES, CONTRACTED WITH BULK TRANSPORTATION AND ERI INC. TO OFF LOAD THE CAR INTO TRUCKS. THE CAR WAS OFF LOADED AND PRESSURE IN THE CAR WAS REDUCED TO 0. THE CAR WAS BAD ORDERED IN THE TUCSON YARD WAITING MOVEMENT APPROVAL FROM THE FRA.

column62: Overfilled; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: MIKE, TRAIN LEAD CARMAN, REPORTED GATX 57866, A LOAD OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID, ENTRAINED TO QWCEW 27, HAD A RUPTURED DISC AND THE TANK WAS WET ON THE TOP. DUFFY EXON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MGR. EXON DISCOVERED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS OVERFILLED TO THE BASE OF THE LIQUID LINE VALVE. THE VALVE BODY WAS TIGHTENED TWO FULL TURNS. THE CAR WAS SET OUT FOR LOAD REDUCTION. MR. EXON ADVISED THAT NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND. RMCC MADE A COURTESY STATE NOTIFICATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JIM BOWERS, CAR FOREMAN, OF TWO LEAKING TANK CARS IN THE 18TH STREET YARD. GATX 68161, A LOAD OF PETROLEUM OIL, WAS REPORTED TO APPARENTLY BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR WITH PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES. UTLX 203206, A LOAD OF ALCOHOL, WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM AN UNDETERMINED LOCATION ON THE TANK CAR. ON ARRIVAL, MR. SEKAVEC ASSESSED BOTH CARS AND DETERMINED THAT THE GATX 68161 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR ONLY. THE CAP WAS REMOVED AND THE VALVE WAS SHUT COMPLETELY AS IT WAS CRACKED SLIGHTLY OPEN. THE GASKET WAS MISSING FROM THE CAP AND A NEW GASKET WAS FORMED FROM GORE-TEX MATERIAL. THE CAP WAS REINSTALLED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED. UTLX 203206 WAS EXAMINED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP. FURTHER ASSESSMENT REVEALED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS ONLY HAND-TIGHT, RELEASING ALCOHOL AND ALLOWING IT TO FLOW DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE PLUG WAS REINSTALLED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. MR. SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER OF THE ALCOHOL, SUN COMPANY, AND ADVISED THEM OF THE PROBLEM WITH THE CAR AND THE CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: JEFF WALKER, MANAGER YARD OPERATION, REPORTED A STRONG ODOR IN THE ALFALFA YARD IN EL PASO, TX. JOHN JACKSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, DETERMINED THAT TANKCAR GETX 3126 RELEASED VAPORS DUE TO THREE OF THE EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS BEING LOOSE. ALSO, THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE VALVE WAS OPEN SLIGHTLY WITH THE PLUG NOT PROPERLY SECURED. MR. JACKSON SECURED AND RELEASED THE CAR TO DESTINATION. ALL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE BY RMCC AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.

column25: A P L LAND TRANSPORT SERV
column168: ICTF SECURITY OFFICER SMITH, REPORTED CONTAINER APLU 997851 LOCATED IN THE ICTF YARD AT THE B/C BREAK OF TRACK #811 WAS NOTED LEAKING AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF HAZMAT MATERIAL FROM THE CONTAINER DOORS. MANAGER COOPER RESPONDED AND REPORTED THE SUBSTANCE WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP CONTAINER APLU 997851, AND DID NOT APPEAR TO BE THE LISTED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. A THICK SUBSTANCE WAS DRIPPING FROM THE REAR DOORS ONTO THE FRONT NOSE OF THE BOTTOM CONTAINER, UGMU 899225. BOTH CONTAINERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE RAIL CAR AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK, WHERE THEY COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE ABOVE CONTAINER, DEVELOPED THERE WERE 5 GALLON METAL PAILS STACKED 2 HIGH ON PALLET AND STRETCH WRAPPED, SEVERAL ROWS IN FROM THE REAR DOORS. USED PALLETS WERE PLACED ADJACENT TO THE LOADED PALLETS TO FILL THE VOIDS. 2X4 LUMBER WAS PLACED IN VARIOUS CONFIGURATIONS, WHICH IS SUPPECTED, TO PREVENT THE OVER ALL LADING FROM MOVING WHILE IN TRANSIT. NONE OF THE LUMBER, NOR THE PALLETS ARE AN APPROVED METHOD FOR PROPER SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES WHILE IN TRANSIT. SEVERAL PALLETS OF STEEL COILS WERE ALSO NOTED FORWARD OF THE PAILS, WITH NO SECUREMENT OR LADING DIVIDERS IN PLACE. UPON REMOVING THE PAILS, IT WAS NOTED THE SHIPPER USED 48 INCH WIDE PALLETS FOR THE PAILS. THIS WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THE PALLETS BEING OFF SET THROUGH OUT THE CONTAINER, AS THEY WILL NOT SET SIDE BY SIDE DUE TO THE OVER SIZE. ONE OF THE PALLETS HAD BEEN POSITIONED WITH THE CORNER RESTING ON THE CORNER OF THE OFF SET FORWARD PALLET, CAUSING PALLET TO BOW. RESULTING SHIFT AND WEIGHT OF THE TOP PAILS CRUSHED 1 PAIL ON THE LOWER TIER. ESTIMATED LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS 4 GALLONS. 9 ADDITIONAL PAILS WERE DAMAGED TO THE POINT THEY WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT. THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE REMAINING DAMAGED PAILS WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT. THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE FREIGHT, INCLUDING THE SALVAGE DRUMS, PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO A LOCAL WAREHOUSE FOR CONSOLIDATION.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: MIKE RAMIREZ, MANAGER, INTERMODAL TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED CONTAINER KKFU 117437 WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD INTERMODAL FACILITY, COMMERCE, CA., AND NOTED A SMALL POOL OF PRODUCT ON THE PAVEMENT(APPROXIMATELY 2-3 GALLONS) BELOW THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER. FIELD TESTING OF THE LIQUID WAS INCONCLUSIVE.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER. ASHLAND CHEMICAL, TO HAVE TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL PERFORM THE REMEDIATION.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF 2 FLOOR LOADED PALLETS AT THE REAR, SECURED BY A SINGLE 2X4 NAILED TO THE FLOOR. A KNEE BRACE WAS CONSTRUCTED BETWEEN THE PALLETIZED LADING AND FLOOR LOADED 55 GALLON  METAL DRUMS TOWARDS THE NOSE. THE DRUMS WERE LOADED IN A 4-3-4 PATTERN AND SECURED AT THE KNEE BRACE WITH TY-GARD RESTRAINT.  THE TY-GARD MATERIAL WAS LOOSE INDICATING THE DRUMS WERE NOT PROPERLY NESTED, OR THE TY-GARD NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED WHEN APPLIED.  WHILE OFF LOADING THE DRUMS, LOCATED 1 DRUM CONTAINING FRUFURYL ALCOHOL, POISON, THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP ROLLING HOOP.  THE DRUM HAD ABRADED AGAINST THE ROLLING HOOP OF AN ADJACENT DRUM, CAUSING A SMALL CRACK IN THE METAL ROLLING HOOP FROM WEAR.  APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. SEVERAL OTHER DRUMS OF NONREGULATED PRODUCT WERE ALSO DAMAGED AND LEAKING IN A SIMILAR MANOR.  THE DAMAGED-LEAKING DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO OVER PACK DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING, INCLUDING THE DAMAGED DRUMS, PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, THEN PROPERLY SECURED FOR OVER THE ROAD MOVEMENT TO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.

MR DENNIS M. JOHNSON, MGR. CTS, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD RECEIVED A REPORT OF TANK CAR UTLX 30000 LEAKING FROM A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR. UPON ARRIVAL AT EL CENTRO, CALIFORNIA MR JOHNSON OBSERVED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM A WELD ON THE SKID PLATE PROTECTING THE SUMP IN THE  BOTTOM OF THE CAR. A TEMPERARY PATCH WAS APPLIED TO THE LEAK AND THE CAR WAS OFF LOADED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR. ON 5-21-2002 MR DEAN COOPER, UNION PACIFIC AND COBY LA PLACE, JONES HAMILTON CONDUCTED AN INTERIOR INSPECTION OF THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE SECURING BRACKET FOR THE LIQUID LINE FILL PIPE HAD COME LOOSE AND WAS LOCATED ABOUT 4 FEET TO THE B END OF THE CAR FROM THE SUMP. THE LIQUID LINE PIPE HAD RUBBED HOLES IN THE LINER AT THE SUMP CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO REACT WITH THE METAL CAUSING THE LEAK. CAR WAS TO BE BILLED AND MOVED TO A TANK CAR REPAIR LOCATION BY JONES HAMILTON.

RICHARD WULFF, MECHANICAL SUPERINTENDANT FOR ALTON SOUTHERN, REPORTED A SLOW LEAK TO CAR PLCX 224322 FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. MR. WULFF STATED HE WOULD BE MOVING IT TO A SECURE LOCATION. JOHN MILLER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MGR. MILLER REPORTED THE BOLTS ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WERE TIGHTENED AND RELEASE WAS STOPPED.

TANKCAR UTLX 99303 REPORTED LEAKING VAPORS FROM TOP OF CAR. MR. JOHN JACKSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE HAD A MINOR VAPOR RELEASE. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND STATED THEY WOULD CONTACT THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOR REPAIRS. STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS  WERE MADE.  RESCAR COMPANIES, EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE DETERIORATED O-RING.  CAR WAS INSPECTED BY MR. JACKSON AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.
WHILE DRIVER WAS WINING UP HOSE NOZZEL CAME ON MECHANIC WENT OUT TO REPAIR NOZZEL.

column168: UMO/BILL BRAY WAS LOADING A PALLET BEHIND THE DRUMS THAT WERE DUNNAGES WITH CARDBOARD NOT WOOD AND WHILE SETTING DOWN THE PALLET ONE OF HIS FORKS PUNCTURED THE BASE OF THE PLASTIC DRUM.

LEROY SKLOSS, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED TANKCAR DCTX 29630 LEAKED A STEADY STREAM OF LIQUID FROM THE TOP. THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED AT YARD ONE. TRACK ONE, AX 340, AT THE SOUTH END OF THE SOUTH SOSAN YARD. PAUL PERSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MGR. PERSON DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM THE LIQUID EDUCATION LINE BALL VALVE STEM PACKING. THE BALL VALVE STEM HAD NO PACKING AROUND THE VALVE STEM HANDLE. PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED AND PACKING WAS APPLIED TO THE VALVE STEM HANDLE. MR. PERSON REPORTED THE RAILCAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED TO REPLACE THE VALVE. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND DUE TO THE HIGH EVAPORATION RATE OF ETHYL ACETATE.

AT 0755HRS ON 5-4-02 CTS MGR LERCH REPONDED TO A REPORTED LEAKING TANK CAR ENTRAINED ON TRAIN QBTWC-03 LOCATED AT MILE POST 29, GLIDDEN SUBDIVISION; ROSENBURG TX. CHECK OF WAYBILL RECORDS IDENTIFIED TANK CAR BIGX 1016 TO BE LOADED WITH ARGON, A NON FLAMMABLE GAS, UN1951. ROSENBERG FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE, HAD TRAFFIC STOPPED ON HWY 90A, AND REPORTED PRODUCT TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR. UPON RECEIVING INFORMATION, MGR LERCH RESPONDED AND WHILE ENROUTE SPOKE TO SHIPPER JOHN REGIER OF AIR LIQUIDE. HE ADVISED THAT A TECHNITION WOULD BE ENROUTE TO INSPECT AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR. UPON ARRIVAL AND INSPECTION OF THE CAR, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM A PARTICALLY OPEN BOTTOM LOADING VALVE. UPON TIGHTENING OF THE VALVE APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TURN, THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED AND CAR WAS SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION. ON ARRIVAL OF AIR LIQUIDE FIELD TECHNITION JERRY SCHOENBAUER,  CAR WAS FURTHER INSPECTED WITH NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED. AT 1125HRS TRAFFIC ON HWY 90A WAS RELEASED AND TRAIN QBTWC-03 WAS CLEARED FOR MOVEMENT. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS INCIDENT.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: FILE: 2223-D, SHIPPER: TOWERY PUBLISHING, AWB# TMA 9132738016 TUP, 1 OF 5 PACKAGES. ON 07/02/2002 AT 03:07 A CALL CAME IN OF A PACKAGE THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING AT DOOR "A-9" BUILDING "A" OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY, LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN ELWOOD BOHL RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION ARRIVING AT 03:22. UPON ARRIVAL TECHNICIAN BOHL OBSERVED A PACKAGE THAT ONLY HAD AN AIRBORNE ROUTING LABEL THAT INDICATED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS PACKAGE #2 OF 6 PACKAGES. THE OTHER  FOUR PACKAGES WERE NOT LOCATED IN THE AREA AND MUST HAVE ALREADY MOVED TO DESTINATION. TECHNICIAN BOHL OPENED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND FOUND MISCELLANEOUS SPICES AND OTHER COOKING PRODUCTS, FURTHER  INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS REVEALED A 1 X 8 OUNCE AEROSOL CAN OF "GREAT VALUE NO STICK COOKING SPRAY"  THE PROTECTIVE CAP HAD SEPARATED FROM THE AEROSOL CAN AND DISPERSED SOME OF THE CONTENTS. IT IS UNKNOWN HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS IN THE AEROSOL CAN AND HOW MUCH WAS LOST. IT WAS NOTED THIS WAS THE ONLY PRODUCT IN THE PACKAGE THAT WAS REGULATED. TECHNICIAN BOHL DOUBLE BAGGED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION AND SENT IT TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT BUILDING WHERE IT WAS PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM AND THEN INTO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING TSA INVESTIGATION. THE OTHER FOUR PACKAGES WERE LOCATED AT THEIR  DESIGNATED DESTINATION AND INSPECTED. THERE WERE NO REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOUND IN ANY OF THE PACKAGES. CLEAR OF SCENE: 03:39

I RESPONDED TO A SPILL ON THE ORANGE BELT. I USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN. RESPONSE SHEET FOR UNKNOWN HAD ME PERFORM A LITMUS TEST. THE LITMUS TEST READ PH 8 BALANCE RANGE. RESPONSE SHEET AND RESULT OF LITMUS TEST HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID. RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAD ME ABSORB ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WITH CLAY ABSORBENT. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRY. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE DUMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. IF THE CORRECT METHOD OF PACKAGE HANDLING WAS PUT TO USE, THIS DAMAGE WOULD NOT HAVE OCCURRED.

THE LITMUS TEST READ PH 13 BALANCE RANGE. RESPONSE SHEET AND RESULT OF LITMUS TEST HAD ME USE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID. RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE HAD ME CAREFULLY APPLY SODIUM BICARBONATE. I RETESTED THE SPILL MATERIAL WITH THE PH TAPE TO ENSURE THAT THE PH WAS WITHIN THE NEUTRAL RANGE OF 6-9. CLAY ABSORBENT WAS ALSO USE TO CONTAIN THE REMAINING CONTAMINATED MATERIAL. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PLACE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY, AND AFTERWARDS ALL MATERIALS WERE THEN TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. column168: AFTER LOADING HIS TRAILER SPINX DRIVER, DAVID MARSHALL LEFT CMP CROFT, TANK FARM. DAVID HAD LOADED 9,002 GALLONS OF FUEL ONTO A 5-COMPARTMENT HEIL TRAILER. DAVID PROCEEDED NORTH ON SR 295 TOWARDS REIDVILLE OR JOHN B WHITE SR BLVD, IN SPARTANBURG SC AT ROUGHLY 0900 DAVID'S CENTER OF GRAVITY CAUSED THE TRAILER TO ROLL OVER AS DAVID WAS MAKING A LEFT HAD TURN, FROM SR 295 N ONTO JBW SR. BLVD. DAVID WAS CITED FOR THE ACCIDENT FROM THE INVESTIGATION OFFICER, JEFF GRANT OF THE SPARTANBURG POLICE DEPT, (864-809-1355). THE CITATION WAS THAT DAVID WAS "GOING TOO FAST FOR CONDITIONS" THE WEATHER WAS CLEAR AND SUNNY ABOUT 78-85 DEGREES. JERRY SPROUSE, FRED ADKINS AND MYSELF DROVE TO THE INCIDENT SITE IN JERRY'S CAR. JUST BEFORE WE LEFT THE CORPORATE OFFICE I MADE AN INITIAL TELEPHONE CALL TO PHILLIPS RECOVERIES, (1-800-947-6805/508 CHEROKEE ROAD, PELZER, SC 29669) TO MEET WITH US AT THE SITE AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. WE MET RICHARD PHIPPS AT THE SITE. WE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AROUND 0935-0940, (DAN COOPER ALSO CAME TO THE SITE, FROM CAPSTONE INSURANCE SERVICES). ROGER TATE LATER CAME FOR FRED TO RETURN TO THE SPINX OFFICES. (LATER GREG MINTON DROVE BACK WITH FRED TO THE SITE, 1830) THERE WAS AN EMERGENCY COMMAND POST AWAY FROM THE 'HOT-ZONE' ON SITE WITH A MAN NAMED COMMANDER CARUSO AS THE SUPERVISOR. MR. CARUSO WAS THE CHIEF OF THE SPARTANBURG FIRE DEPT. MR. CARUSO HAD ENLISTED THE AID OF OTHER FIRE DEPARTMENTS, A HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM AND AN EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS TEAM ALL BEFORE WE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  DAVID WAS TRAPPED IN THE CAB. TODD TEAL FROM 105 ROBBIE COURT,MAYO, S.C. ASSISTED DAVID FROM THE CAB BY BREAKING THE WINDSHIELD FOR AN EMERGENCY EXIT. MR. TEAL WORKS FOR HOPPER PEST CONTROL OF SPARTANBURG AND MAY BE REACHED AT 864-461-0649 AN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE CALLED JBR ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, (210 ALICE STREET/SPARTANBURG SC), HAD ALREADY BEGAN 'CLEAN-UP'. THE MAN REPRESENTING JBR WAS NAMED REX RUSSELL, (864-583-2727). MR RUSSELL PLACED DIRT BARRIERS ON JBW SR BLVD TO DIVERT THE FUEL INTO A 4,000-5000 GALLON VACUUM TRUCK. HE ALSO PLACED (3) WORK CREW IN THE LOCAL CREEK TO PREVENT 500-1000 GALLONS FORM SPREADING PAST A 1,000-FOOT STRETCH OF CREEK. A SECOND VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED HERE. TOTAL GALLONS COLLECTED WAS 28,000 GALLONS/6,000 GALLONS SENT TO ALLIED IN ALABAMA FOR DISPOSAL. PHILLIPS RECOVERIES BROUGHT 4 MEN, (1) SERVICE TRUCK, PLUS MIKE AND VICKIE PHILLIPS. WHEN COMMANDER CARUSO RELEASED PHILLIPS TO ATTEND THE TANKER, THEY DRILLED HOLES IN THE (3) CENTER COMPARTMENTS TO PUMP OFF THE REMAINING FUEL. JERRY CALLED DEARYBURY AND ASKED AN ALTERNATE TANKER COME AND ASSIST WITH THIS FUEL. DRIVER DAVID CAMP CAME TO ASSIST, (864-357-7467). MR CAMP DELIVERED THE SAVED FUEL FROM THE WRECK SPINX TRAILER. PHILLIPS RECOVERIES COMPLETED THEIR DRILLING JUST BEFORE 1645. (2) BROKEN DRILL BITS HAD TO BE REPLACED. THE FOAM TRUCK WAS ALSO BROKEN DOWN TWICE, (MAYBE (2) HOURS TOTAL DELAY). NO PROGRESS COULD BE MADE WITHOUT THE ASSISTANCE OF THE FOAM TRUCK. THE SPINX TANKE
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis
